  abstract = {On the 28th of February 2010, the storm Xynthia flooded several low urbanized areas on the French Atlantic coast. This major marine flood directly caused the death of 41 people. These areas were first classified as ``areas of extreme danger'' and then as ``black zones''. A semantic analysis is conducted in this work as this expression of ``black zone'' introduces a new level of danger on the maps made by the State. This paper presents a critical analysis of the criteria that were used for these definitions and is applied to the town of La Faute-surMer in the d\'epartement of Vendee, a recently urbanized territory. The houses located within the classified zones were first purchased by the State and are now gradually destroyed. This fallback strategy is relatively recent in the French management of flooded territories and is not without raising difficulties. Performed in emergency after Xynthia, this policy, which aims to prevent further victims, should always be implemented on the national territory without waiting for a disaster.},
